nt||HT|d|at|
^B@2^Y@3In addition to the ordinary echo given along with the other fundamental principles (in Part I), there are two other interesting and occasionally useful echoes, or conventional discards. They consist of a |CP|8|AT|trump echo|CP||AT| and a |CP|8|AT|no-trump echo|CP||AT|. |
PG| ***** 1 ***** |


AT|

In Auction Bridge, the trump echo was known as “^*Ithe three-card  peter^*N," |CP|8|AT| * |CP||FP||AT| and was always used to inform Partner of the fact that three trumps were held. For example, if a defensive player held, in the trump suit, the eight, five and deuce, he would play the five-spot on the first lead of trumps, and follow with the deuce on the second round, to convey the information that an additional trump was held. If he failed to use this echo, his failure told his Partner that he held originally either two trumps or four.|
PG| ***** 2 ***** |


cp|8|AT|
^B@2^Y@3* |CP||AT|The word ^*Ipeter^*N as used here has no relation to the masculine name Peter. The origin may be traced back to the ^*Iblue peter^*N a trump signal (calling for a trump lead from Partner) used in Whist, which was so called from the nautical term ^*Iblue peter^*N, a corruption of ^*I"blue repeater^*N," used in signaling with flags. The ^*I"three-card peter^*N" was merely a loose modification of the original Whist term, to indicate a signal made in the trump suit, but not to induce Partner to lead trumps.—Sam Fry, Jr.|
pg| ***** 3 ***** |


at|
^B@2^Y@3The experience of Contract players has modified this convention to make it more useful. At Contract Bridge, a player should not echo in trumps simply because he held three of them originally, but he should confine his echoing to show ability to ruff some side suit.|
PG| ***** 4 ***** |


